The paper deals with the problem of dictionary learning, which is a common topic in machine learning and signal processing. The use of autoencoders and ReLU activation functions suggests a focus on deep learning and neural networks, which are typically covered in the cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-categories. The mention of experiments with synthetic data and the use of ReLU gates to recover the support of sparse codes suggests a focus on computer vision and image processing, which are covered in the cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) sub-category. The use of optimization techniques and the analysis of gradient descent suggest a focus on information theory and optimization, which are covered in the cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-category. Finally, the mention of experimental evidence and the use of statistical analysis suggest a focus on statistical inference and data analysis, which are covered in the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category.
